{
  "doc_id": "3950",
  "text": "The results of this fMRI study are in line with predictions by the social motivation hypothesis [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] : Compared to TDCs, youth with ASD had stronger reward system responses for CIs mostly within the non-social realm (e.g., video games) than social rewards (e.g., approval). Additionally, aberrant reward system responses-most pronounced within the caudate nucleus-were related to greater social impairment. Behavioral task performance did not differ between the two study groups, emphasizing the power of neurobiological data in revealing atypical motivational mechanisms in ASD and at the same time avoiding a potential confounding factor [CITATION_3] .",
